According to Tenn. Code Ann. § 56-2-1006:

(a) A licensee may notify consumers residing in Tennessee whose nonpublic information has been acquired by a cybersecurity event through three methods of notice:
   1) Written notice;
   2) Electronic notice, consistent with electronic records and signatures set forth in 15 U.S.C. § 7001, or by email if the primary method of communication with the consumer has been electronic;
   3) Substitute notice, which includes email notice, posting on the licensee's website, and notification to major statewide media.

response_8:
Tennessee:
According to Tenn. Code Ann. § 56-2-1006:

The acceptable methods of notice of a data breach in Tennessee are:
1) Written notice;
2) Electronic notice, if the notice provided is consistent with the provisions regarding electronic records and signatures set forth in 15 U.S.C. § 7001, or if the licensee's primary method of communication with the consumer has been by electronic means. Electronic means may include email notification;
3) Substitute notice, if the licensee demonstrates that the cost of providing notice would exceed two hundred fifty thousand dollars ($250,000), the affected class of subject persons to be notified exceeds five hundred thousand (500,000) persons, or the licensee does not have sufficient contact information. Substitute notice consists of email notice, conspicuous posting of the notice on the licensee's website, and notification to major statewide media.

